The Prague Stock Exchange fell into a negative at the end of the trade
After the morning sharp collapse, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected the losses.
CEZ shares transactions reached almost half of the daily business.
The Prague Stock Exchange followed its Monday slump as it declined by almost six percent right from the start of Tuesday's trade.
This time, the downturn is behind the fall in shares on Wall Street.
Here, too, the market's response to the result of the U.S. House of Representatives vote, which refused to support the plan to stabilise the financial sector there.
The fall of shares in Asia
A dramatic fall on Tuesday experienced stock on stock exchanges in Asia, although indices but over the course of the day some losses eventually erased.
The Hang Seng Exchange index in Hong Kong wrote off almost four percent during trade, but later deleted some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stock on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, dropped by 3.8 percent, in Shanghai the markets were closed.
Sydney Stocks lost more than five percent, but ultimately reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
According to the Taiwanese index, the stock exchange dropped by 3.6 percent.
"The timing of the rescue action in the US is uncertain and it will affect financial markets worldwide," noted Hong Kong monetary bureau chief Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines monetary policy separately, i.e. without depending on China's central bank.
Hong Kong's interest rates are at the same level as the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should quickly return to negotiations and propose support for the financial system.
Otherwise, it is said that other countries will also feel the effects.
American Stock Blood Bath
The U.S. House of Representatives rejected Monday's plan to support the financial system, for which up to $700 billion was to be spent (nearly 12 trillion CZK).
Lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indices recorded the biggest fall in over 20 years.
The Dow Jones index declined by almost seven percent and recorded a drop in a similar range for the last time in 1987.
The index had fallen before the vote, but once it became clear that the motion in the House had failed, the index found itself in a free fall.
Congress retreated: US government can pump $700 billion into banks
U.S. Congressional leaders and President George W. Bush's government have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the US financial system.
The vote will be the beginning of next week.
American legislators made a breakthrough in talks about approving the rescue plan in the form of financial assistance for the US financial system of $700 billion (approximately 12 trillion crowns).
But the game is not yet won.
Congressmen must complete some details of the agreement before they can publish the final form of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed at the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services of the Barney Frank House told Reuters.
According to sources, the Senate could vote on the plan at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first major psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
However, there will then be a "sobriety" thanks to the complexity of mechanisms to help markets achieve even in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have solved our differing views on the form of the package to stabilise the market," said Democrat Nancy Pelosi for Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still take place on Sunday.
Lawmakers' representatives met US Finance Minister Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give a definitive form to the government fund.
This should buy unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which drag financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective on the market.
We still need to continue our recovery plan, but I think we are there," Paulson said.
Signal for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis is affecting stock markets that are falling sharply.
According to Nevada's Democratic Senator Harry Reid, the legislators are so keen to reach a definitive agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before trading on Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone, where Congressional decisions could affect Monday's trade.
However, it is not yet clear with certainty when both chambers of the U.S. Congress will vote on the law, nor whether they can be stuck to a problem at the last minute.
Lawmakers hope to be approved in the next few days.
However, the law will admit a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, in a succession of another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush appreciated progress in negotiations
Although the President may veto this decision, Congress may overrule its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to raise funds to buy out bad mortgage securities whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, remained preserved.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
U.S. President Bush is also satisfied with the progress of the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto stated that Bush is satisfied with Saturday's progress and appreciates "a two-party effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitation of gold parachutes
Senate bank committee chairman Christopher Dodd, the negotiator's head, said the legislators agreed on responsibility for the money program, protection of taxpayers from losses, closure of reliefs, timing of financing the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit so-called gold parachutes for directors of companies participating in the programme and establishes a committee to supervise the fund.
That should be run by the Treasury.
"We have worked very hard on this and we have made great progress towards an agreement that will work and be useful to the market and to all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also counts on help for homeowners who have problems paying off.
The government should negotiate new repayments for mortgages it buys in order to reduce the monthly repayment costs for debtors and allow them to retain their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to chief economist Patrio Finance David Mark, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"This is because it is not known what mechanism and at what price the troubled assets will be bought out.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and government will divide their losses," Marek told iHned.cz this week.
If the plan is approved now or at the beginning of next week, Mark says it's not that important.
"It is much more important that this week the Congressmans agree to support this plan and to sanctify it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on approval is most important at the moment," Marek emphasized.
Knife blade fight: MP3 players against mobile phones.
We will advise on how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
That seems to make it clear that it's better to just buy a phone.
Still, there are enough reasons to get a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the manner of use and demands of the future owner.
It's hard to get a top-notch high-end record player to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all, such music products on LP boards do not work out and there is no objective reason in qualitative terms for this.
However, if your shelves contain vinyl with art rock, jazz or blues, you may at least dream of such a gramophone.
It is the same with music on the road, i.e. music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, as well as a Pink Floyd fan it may be hard to chew the headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also determines battery stamina
Some top-notch music players can do much more than just play music, but what most cell phones can't do.
No current device is as versatile as a phone.
Besides primary functions, phone calls and texting, he can play music and video, record both, have a better, worse camera, and maybe even navigate.
And considering smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph anything.
The versatility of a cell phone also brings disadvantages.
The more features you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the display sends you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten twelve hours, usually much less.
In this direction, music players (especially the simplest) are significantly more powerful.
With cheap phones, therefore, count on them not to play for more than a few hours.
If you make any more calls here and there, get one more charger to work just to be sure - that's also true of the more expensive devices.
With MP3 players you will not have this problem, even the worse will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation per charge.
Another problem arises when you record music on your phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on a memory card, but few card readers can handle miniature memory cards that are used in mobile phones without reduction.
You do not need any special software for players except for exceptions (iPod).
All you have to do is fill the device with USB music from the computer.
Most mobile phones and players will already create a music library by the name of the performer, album name, genre or user evaluation.
Some devices display only the tree structure of directories similar to the Explorer in Windows and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Players are easier to operate, mobile phones are more skilled
When selecting a specific device, be particularly interested in battery life, memory capacity, quality and sound output type and, of course, control comfort.
If music is primarily a set for you and if you listen to it every day just briefly on the tram, you just need any mobile phone that plays MP3.
Which is what almost any cell phone can do.
You don't even have to watch too much of what music formats a cell phone or player can do.
MP3 can handle all and the vast majority of the music that gets to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely distributed and besides it, the vast majority of instruments can also handle music in WMA format.
AAC occurs less (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also allow, for example, to purchase music online.
Simply visit the respective operator's website (or other provider) via mobile internet and purchase a song or album.
This service could already in itself be a strong argument for getting a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is lousy and is mostly limited to fast-fermented radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
In general, however, it is assumed that this method of selling music (whether through GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their phones around all the time.
Whenever you want to hear something, you feel the phone in your pocket while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least wire handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated speaker that has almost every mobile phone, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Perhaps the greatest advantage of music phones will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones are normally below three thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns, you'll have a very decent walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of output to common headphones.
The best and technically the most equipped phones, even with a 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15,000.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy to operate.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can be controlled by everyone.
Minimum functions, similar control with a previously common tape recorder or perhaps a gramophone is obvious.
There is no collision in the form of a accidentally turned on mobile internet and subsequently a giant data transfer account.
What devices to reach for
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchange memory cards (type M2, microSD etc.).
Even with the purchase of the relevant card, you can fit into 2,000 crowns.
Be careful, though.
Only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported for basic models.
Only the most expensive ones can handle 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach for Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iraver.
According to capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, you better reach for specialized phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokies and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of the operator is thus close to a separate MP3 player.
It is in the Sony Ericsson sector, whose walkman mobiles have the same user interface as individually sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to CZK 4,000, but with more memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), will take MP3 players away from the above mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services such as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet there's something missing here - a virtual operator who would make the classics cheaper.
Maybe he won't be long.
We have written on Mobil.cz many times about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
After all, CTÚ confirmed this, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming charges regulation, this may lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to get into the fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetrations over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to pretend that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who has said several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that the classic operator with his own network probably no longer has a chance (after all, he would probably be hard to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought significant price reductions, which classical operators also had to respond to.
Prior to the entry of pikes such as Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile, similar voices were heard in the UK as in our country.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we do not have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to concentrate on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to function effectively, they need much less customers than a classic operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, even a bet on an innovative target group can be quite a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"Administrative guys vote Mobilking - operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is hard to say if a similar concept as in Poland could follow us.
Vodafone's press secretary Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offering."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations do not look very promising in the Czech Republic.
Mobilking will rather be launched in other countries of our region," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything they can to prevent any potential competitor from developing.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator is no longer hidden by the GTS Novera Group, which would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only solid but mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have discussed this possibility repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already made progress in negotiations," says the group's press secretary Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe it's a better time, then.
From unofficial information it seems that the first virtual operator should be looking forward to maybe by the end of the year.
For now, however, its emergence is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň of the O2 Telefónika Press Department said in his comments.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press secretary Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with O2 statement: "So far, we have not recorded any viable and mutually advantageous business project on which to build further."
And he adds, "It's hard for any virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have had to have a concrete agreement on the table in order to consider this short term."
Vodafone's paying attention to meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider most beneficial from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - one hand with operators
The procedure of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a fall in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
Why, then, make it easier for such a competitor to make it easier?
The fact that when operators do something, they are able to pull together is also demonstrated by the tensions around the formation of U:fona.
Probably the biggest pressure towards CTU went at the time of the formation of U:fona from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the CTU website.
But now U:phone is useful as an argument why not allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile market was recently enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would lay high requirements on him and, above all, on his services."
Due to this approach of mobile operators, however, it is directly striking by the complete lack of interest of Czech regulatory authorities.
It is not just the position of CTÚ, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - has no power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical stand on the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between a mobile operator and a virtual operator to rent the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," Kristián said in response to our inquiry to Kristián Chalupa from the ÚOHS External Relations Department.
It may not surprise operators’ representatives of such a formulated statement.
From an office to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market, it is more than considered.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds, "In a foreign country, where virtual operators operate normally, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are probably not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
In fact, the shock of the entire case is the touching alignment of three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, if it really is just a coincidence, is offered entirely by itself.
Like the exact same price of petrol at gas stations, it is certainly just the result of chance and hard competitive struggle.
"The Authority did not find signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this matter, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore they do not have adequate increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are probably missing the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said.
Interpretation of dominant position on the market is one of many disputed points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by CTU, according to which telecommunications is the only market in terms of competition.
Of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different perspective - it is always necessary to agree with the network operator to create a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator - it has quite logically - a monopoly on its network.
So in a particular segment, it necessarily has to be dominant.
Even if we do not allow this argument, it should be at least a warning for ÚOHS that three mobile operators are doing similarly.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including that of GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in dealing with all operators.
The holding of responsibility at CTU is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications, which the ÚOHS puts away from the whole matter.
We've met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recent amendment to the Telecommunication Act, the extension of CTU's powers to telecommunications competition has failed to enforce, although many experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's okay when no one's watching
The operation of some pseudovirtual operators, several of which exist in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies issuing their own mobile telephone service price lists, but they are only partially public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile telephone services.
Prices of these companies usually only get to the chosen ones.
The trick is that the company performs as a classic company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, he will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar sales.
"If there were any cases you are talking about, this could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would be dealing with and could result in the end of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is unlikely that similar activity would not have come to the responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators shall prevent such a procedure.
In fact, these companies have significant profits and, unlike actual virtual operators, they do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law of similar speculation allows, however, the services of these companies use only a negligible percentage of customers.
Moreover, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not kept in their name, so they cannot have it fully with them as common customers of mobile operators."
But that's what the CTU should be at least weird.
In addition, another question is open for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively strong powers to detect similar activities, and, if it does not want to, it may not be satisfied with the operators' explanation that they have no idea of such activities and their terms of trade forbid it.
When We Won't Be Most Precious
As has been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable drop in prices for services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators were formed, classical operators tried to defend their creation more or less.
Jimi's arguments used were virtually identical - too small or too saturated market, problems with quality of services etc.
In developed countries, however, regulatory authorities, which defended the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers, have intervened at these very times.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator and they were packing more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators switch the whole case like a hot potato.
In our experience, we cannot shake the impression that the ambiguity in competence is more than useful to them in these cases.
But let's not throw a gun in the rye.
If the background information is correct and the virtual operator really soon shows up, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If any of the operators admitted the emergence of a virtual mobile operator, it will hardly be possible for ÚOHS to remain indifferent to rejecting (discrimination) other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling out more than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Select the best
Listen to four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented new recordings of the state anthem Where my home was.
The hymn was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the leadership of Jiří Bělohlovka.
There are four versions - with male or female solo singing, in choral submission and instrumental wording.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka took the lead.
The authors of the anthem's modifications are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymens.
He told Czech Radio earlier that he deliberately chose singers with young representative voices that are distinctive and popular for singing solo variants.
"From the beginning, I tried to be careful with both of them and then also with the congregation to have a clear indication, so that the text could be well understood, so that they could be congruent," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate the 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where my home sounded for the first time in 1834 on the boards of the Estate Theatre in the original Czech play of Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
She gained popularity, and people spontaneously took her for their own.
The first verse of the song then became a natural part of the state anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
One of the seven state symbols remained after the formation of a separate Czech Republic.
