Prague public transport will take the first time on a chip on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will enter the metro, tram and buses, who will have an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At this point, it can buy roughly 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) while having their chip card recorded at the information centres and workplaces of the Transport Company in the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Coupons can also be purchased from yesterday via the Internet on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
Over 400 customers made use of the service by afternoon hours.
Those who start using the online store can definitely forget about the delivery windows in the metro stations where they have so far had to stand regularly in long queues for paper tickets.
The coupon will be purchased via the Internet and uploaded to the Opencard card in one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"At these places, the passenger desk with a trained service is available to help those interested in buying online and also uploads a purchased coupon to their card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic coupons to Opencard also in self-service automatas, which are mounted in several metro vestibules.
What do automates look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket marks and passengers may have noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltava.
"There are now five in the city, but there should be eighty by the end of the year," he added.
The coupon checks the driver's seat of the automatic
The vending machine service that starts to work tomorrow is simple.
All you have to do is insert the Opencard chip card into it and the coupon previously paid will upload itself to it.
Electronic coupons are valid not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings as of tomorrow.
Thus, on suburban trains and bus lines with the number 300 to 499, by which the capital is driven mainly by the inhabitants of Central Bohemia municipalities.
"On trains included in Prague Integrated Transport, conductors are equipped with card readers, using which they detect both the time and band validity of coupons," explained Filip Drápal of Ropid organization, which sets timetables for Prague public transport.
The suburban buses have card readers built in the driver's box office.
When entering, it is necessary not only to show the chip card to the driver, but it is also necessary to attach Opencard to the designated location on the side of the cash register.
This checks the validity of recorded coupons.
"If passengers need to verify the validity of recorded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal added.
Passengers who do not take suburban buses and will not remember when the coupon expires can go back to self-service slot machines where coupons are recorded on the card.
Here, information about the validity of their documents will be displayed on the display of the apparatus.
The Sudetens wanted a referendum from the U.S.
The Sudeten Germans in 1945 requested the inclusion of Sumava to the United States.
It results from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Science Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America at least.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans reportedly turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is due, among other things, to a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is today stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Science Library.
The Germans from Český Krumlov ask in a letter to the U.S. President not to allow the return of the "Sumava County" - taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly, and we want to be sure in words that American troops come into German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," says the letter, signed by the words "People to whom the fate of Sumava lies at heart".
Since joining Czechoslovakia is said to give Sudeten Germans - in knowledge of the Czech national nature - hope only for brutality, recklessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of a letter from the U.S. President to take over Šumava for the present and eternal times.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of a quarter million residents, you would admit this territory to a foreign country that oppresses and disproves minorities and nothing, has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter states.
The reason why authors cannot sign is said to be a fear of the vindictiveness of the "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the US allegedly doubted the thinking of the Shumava Germans, it was enough for him to hold a referendum in the Šumava County on whether its inhabitants wanted to become part of the US or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound a little naive in today’s knowledge of postwar history, according to some of the survivors it appropriately illustrates the expectations of the Sudeten Germans.
