Even rats have feelings
When a rat or a cockroach escapes danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux believes that even many animals have feelings.
But how could it be checked that they feel the same way when they behave like we do?
For several years, the Internet magazine "Edge" has published contributions from well-known scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in his series selected answers to the question "What do you consider true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove it until now, when we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, once we begin to engage in a different kind and open up questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter an impassable terrain because hardware does not match.
When a rat gets in danger, he does what many other animals do: he pretends to be dead, flees or attacks.
People behave similarly, some scientists conclude on comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe in that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to animal life.
This is because circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include side prefrontal cortex (due to its share in short-term memory and performance or control functions).
This vast area is considerably more developed in man than in other primates, and appears to be missing from other creatures.
At least with those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, between them the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is different even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could conceal the linguistic nature of man: since so much of his perception is associated with the language, it is often said that consciousness depends on him.
In this case, we could rule out animals.
But even if the knowledge of the language did not matter, it would certainly be influenced by the language, so that animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably differ from most of our states of consciousness.
That's why it's difficult to figure out what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, neither can be measured nor, because of special hardware, analysed based on our own experience, it puts us in great trouble to explore it.
Most of my connections relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically more accessible.
It would be possible to examine processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in short-term memory studies in primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick have been engaged in, focuses more on neural correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the importance of the non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I deduce that an emotional system, such as a fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activities.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) utilizes the operating memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely intertwined with those areas of the cortex that feature primates, and especially humans.
In conjunction with linguistic nature, there is a subtle separation of perception, because using words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states to attribute them to others alongside ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the areas of cortex and brain stem devoted to physical feelings, similar to Jaak Pankseep, which, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could easily participate in feelings perceived by multiple animal genera.
In theory, I cannot resist this, but I find it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to us in rats and humans to be fear is likely felt by both organisms as well: But how can it be verified, does Pankseep further say whether rats and humans feel the same way when they behave similarly?
Cockroach flees from danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the conformity of experience.
True, the neural comparison moves us on: rats and humans have brain strains similar to cockroaches and brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for feelings?
And even if it were possible to prove it in man: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And since their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness rests on special circuits and on the tongue), I prefer to examine emotional behavior rather than emotional perception of rats.
Anyway, in this case, we can look forward to progress on the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
As with rats, I don't examine language and consciousness, I don't explore feelings, I don't know if they exist.
It can be considered shortsighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than to repeatedly hurl myself against the wall.
I'm a practical emotionalist.
