Pride and Obstacles of the Life of Blacks in a Separate City
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of Greater Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy, and huge, lies a quiet city in which the pride and intensity of African-American life comes to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black town to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the town of five lakes, three croquet courses, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, enough guava, two schools, and no prison."
Now it's a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville festival Zora! to pay homage to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a party, although she made it a stop for tourists by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers Project of the Depression.
He is still as independent, dignified and private as he was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their real feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, in the year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for open debate on races, many local residents remain cautious of foreign views.
"We pay great attention to how our story is told," says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and exertion.
It is both a historical model of the black rise and a community of nearly 2400 people, where poverty rates are twice as high as the national average.
It is a centre of literature, but also oaks shaded by an example of Southern rural Negro culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that originated from American slavery.
It is not surprising that the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the worry about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way to say Hurston here.
She presented her hometown to the world through hearty books full of dialects such as "Mules and Men (Muly and Men)" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God (their eyes watched God)" (1937).
The five paragraphs of the Florida tourist guide changed the town a bit into Route 17, which runs through the often ephemeral center of Florida, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With the shock of a great drum in life and literature, Hurston introduced readers to the store of the first Eatonville mayor Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road," she wrote, "is a white brown-decorated modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller always takes care of, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits into an hour-long hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston Eatonville connected with self-government, but also with illiteracy, re-marriage, and sex.
Obviously, this wasn't a typical Fodor's publishing house.
It wasn't really a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora said it the way it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls' choirs, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chipper eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Florida Jacksonville.
Seventy - seven - year - old Augustus Franklin recalls that most of the time, when she stormed into town, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevy, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is proud of dignified clothing.
Most residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many laughed.
"The people of Zoru have always been happy to see," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "it never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were removed from the press.
Eatonville seemed to forget her and the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood its significance for the world or its legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's biography "Wrapped in Rainbows (Packed in Rainbows)" published in 2003.
Change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to stretch the city's five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, a local two-lane main road.
The discovery of Orlando has already pushed Interstate Highway 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still getting out of a complicated historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the struggle to stir races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At the time, a bunch of white guys, they came and threw oranges and stuff at people who sat on the side," Franklin said.
"In fact, we had a lady who was killed.
They threw melon out of the car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration and for his decision in the Brown case against the Education Chamber stated that he was "offensive to my race rather than celebrating."
Residents now claim that the desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of local youth.
"Black children were used to hugs - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the non-profit group Preserve the Eatonville Community (Save Eatonville Community).
This lasted until the teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You don't hug your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there's a cultural barrier," said Miss Nathiri.
However, civil rights helped create room for many other Zory Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with reckless self-confidence and quotes such as "How can one deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to the unmarked grave of Hurston and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, he came to the shelves in bookstores praised by Robert E. Hemenway's biography of Hurston, who reclassified her to the American Canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville's most famous daughter found the ramp's lights again.
Former Hurston neighbors now considered her a savior.
To show what can happen to its highway destroy, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return to celebrate.
After a few years, the state retreated from the highway design.
"The five currents of the highway revived, you would say that it directly detonated, real civic pride," said Nathiri.
Boyd said it more simply, "Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory over the highway project helped change the city's image.
Extra-urban like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began going to the local church in 1993, began to appear in more numbers, and residents began to rethink the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historic Register in 1998.
The new single-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 at the re-favoured and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes act as a dark alley in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today is 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come to seek the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated cautiously.
Permission for most interviews must be given in advance and certain things - like murals in the oldest Eatonville church painted by white people and depicting black people in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Jones, a courageous, confident teacher who likes deep red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as the Hurston Festival increased, domestic pride also increased.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems and so on, but not better, not worse, and equally proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
From the voice of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, sincere love for the community sounds when she plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in a local government or a police force she says would use some help.
And even younger ones, such as eleven - year - old twins from Winter Park Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just pass through here, think, 'Hmm, this town is nothing against the others,' said Alondra Kenon recently on Sunday after church.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a while, it's a very nice town."
