Drivers caught repeatedly with alcohol in their blood will have to install "alcolock"
The Interior Ministry requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol have to install a system in his vehicle to prevent him from starting his car drunk or if he does not breathe.
The proposal was already known in June of this year and is now included in the annual report of the Attorney General, according to which it is a pilot project that lasts one year.
Its aim is to get the driver behind the wheel, which is why drivers will also have to take a course in transport reeducation.
In addition to the National Authority for Transport Safety, the General Directorate of Transport (DGT) and the Institute of Technology for Car Safety (FITSA) Foundation will participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 % of car drivers charged more than once for drunk driving will again get behind the wheel in this state.
Alcolock should prevent this because it is a vehicle-connected system that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe before or if the alcohol concentration is higher than the permitted concentration.
Its price exceeds EUR 1,000 and would have to be paid by the culprit himself.
A study conducted in this sense in the US in 2007 showed that in respect of vehicles equipped with this equipment, the offences decreased by 65% during the first year since the introduction.
In Spain, 115 people are expected to be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it results in a criminal offence.
And in order to help implement it, as legislation can be carried out in the usual way, the necessary regulation of criminal provisions, however, requires a change of law.
The equipment is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although it has already been installed in some industrial vehicles and public service vehicles.
Tomorrow, the Congress of Members will vote on the PSOE proposal (Spanish Workers' Socialist Party), in which it is recommended to install this system on school buses, as is the case in France.
