Talking in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean the ones who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but the kids who talk while they're sleeping.
The first time this happens, it might scare you, but it's actually meaningless.
It is a harmless sleep disorder called the somnolnoquia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure you've told more than one of you that he spoke in his sleep last night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadicly (for example once a lifetime in high fevers), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There's only one reason to explain her coming in.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, nightmares, enuresis nocturna (night wetting) or sleepwalking, but it may not be.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fever, stress or distraught situations.
In any case, this is a little underexplored phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or quite the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where he manifests himself with great strength, it would be advisable to observe and consult an expert to see if he has any problems that cause him great anxiety and this is how he manifests himself.
We said it was a harmless disorder, therefore it is not treated unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
However, we can do that by keeping in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Trying not to upset the child too much before going to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent television programs or series.
In very nervous children and those who can work to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
When the somnolyquies appear, try to remain calm.
Recall that she is harmless to the child and that she will remember nothing of what happened the next day.
Useful Advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless because he's not conscious and you're gonna interrupt his sleep.
Even when he talks, he sleeps, and he rests.
Remember, if several times in a row you feel that they are very troubled, it would be advisable to seek advice or to find out what causes such anxiety in a child.
If it is understood what he says (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to interrogate him and extract information from him.
It won't do any good, because when she's asleep, she's not conscious enough to get her thoughts straight.
Moreover, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming of, and therefore why he is saying it, so be very careful how you interpret information and what conclusions you are reaching.
