The presidential visit comes at the same time as the General Assembly of the 'crisis committee' created by Breton fishermen in order to take action against a sharp increase in oil prices, which reached a peak exceeding an average of EUR 1.14 per litre.
According to Elysian Palace spokesman David Martinon, the President will "talk to them about solutions that can be imagined in an effort to help their companies regain competitiveness and better secure employment and payout of sailors".
Nicolas Sarkozy is expected by fishermen with tenacity.
On Tuesday morning, they performed an operation "snake" (an operation of slow-moving vehicles) in the departments of Morbihan and Calvados, causing nearly 10 km traffic jam.
The recreational port in Quiberon was also blocked, but the connections in the direction of Belle-île were not interrupted.
A filter dam was opened on the Quiberon Peninsula.
Sailors demonstrated their determination as early as Monday, with demonstrations taking place in Concarneau and Saint-Brieuc in front of the ports' fuel depots in Brest and Lorient.
The movement spread to other ports on the Atlantic coast and the canal of la Manche, such as the Sables d'Olonne in Vendée, where the trawlers remained in the port, or to Le Havre, where about twenty vessels blocked the operation of merchant ships.
Fishermen from Turballe and from Croisic in the Loire-Atlantique area stopped during the evening a blockade of the important Total Refinery in Donges.
Those from Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait until they eventually decided to act, until Wednesday's meeting at the Ministry.
In Guilvinec, on Tuesday, the "crisis committee" is to decide on how to continue the road, and on its participation in the upcoming meeting at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
However, some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by leaders of the State Department of Fisheries, which did not support their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "fishers will not drop anything" and "they do not want to come to Paris", said Liliane Cariou, Chairman of the Lorient Fisheries Department, for example.
Professional fishermen who do not pay oil tax are currently paying around 50 cents per litre, but they consider that the ship's profitability threshold is only achieved when the oil is below EUR 0.30 per litre.
