They do not believe that this regime, which has been friendly to foreign observers in order to resume negotiations with the European Union, would be ready to make a turn towards democracy.
The sanctions, including the visa ban for 40 Belarusian sexes and the freezing of certain assets, could be abolished if the election is considered clean by observers.
According to the opposition, that was not the case.
"We were kept away from the electoral commissions and our observers were not allowed to participate in the vote census," Juri Potemkin, a spokesman for the Union of Democratic Forces, complained about a diverse group of twelve parties.
"This is a cosmetic change," stresses Alexandr Milinkievich, a former opposition candidate in the 2006 presidential election and the leading personality of the pro-European movement, "because the important thing is who tallies the votes, and in our country it is executive power.
If any opposition Members get into parliament, it will be by being appointed and not elected.
However, their entry into parliament can mean space on television, meetings in regions and bills."
The opposition therefore feels obliged to participate in the political functioning, because "a dialogue with the European Union needs to be started.
