The night's silence once again took hold of the October square.
On television, President Lukashenko and members of the Central Election Commission congratulate themselves on success.
Interview - Blood That Is Again Certain
Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of the foundation yesterday, and his president, Dr Francine Décary, rightly rejoiced, as Hema-Québec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the state blood reserve administered by the Canada Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and wave of public displeasure, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Kráter, which aimed to explain the circumstances leading to such a tragedy, and to formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not be repeated again.
While Judge Kráter was stalling to submit a report, some provinces set in motion a committee whose aim was to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this role was played by the Gélinea Committee.
After Gélineau and Kráter's report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, who was to be managed by Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply all provinces and both territories.
"When Hema-Québec launched its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system," recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was depressing.
With a consistent effort to increase the safety of blood products and constant work in this area over the years, we have regained public confidence," Hema-Québek said, proudly adding that by early 2008 almost 94% of the Québek population had trusted.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its founding on September 28, 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
"Then we have seen many cases of human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of a disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says the woman who has been leading the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea whether this disease could spread through blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of Kráter and Gélineau's report, according to which, if we do not know this and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by the degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, exclusionary measures must be taken.
Thus, in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who have stayed in the United Kingdom since 1980 for more than one month.
A few years ago, it was then safely proven that this disease was transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to stick to the principle of prudence."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for HIV virus detection appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests that allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in donor blood rather than the presence of antibodies based on tests previously used.
NAT tests have allowed the deaf period to be shortened between the moment the patient is infected and the moment our techniques in the blood can be exposed by the first viruses, the specialist explains.
We managed to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have substantially reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing and without finding out.
These improvements allowed the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions to be significantly reduced.
Today, one person in 12 million is exposed to the risk of receiving HIV - contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission via a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe a blood transfusion necessary to heal," says Hema-Québek's head of management.
"The challenge for the next decade is to preserve the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of disease element can appear in the system.
Just last year, a chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by insect stings.
We need to be constantly cautious," Dr. Décary continues, stressing that aside from safe supply, Hema-Québec must also count on sufficient supply.
"The needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive treatment for cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Québečany permitted to donate."
Any healthy person at least 18 years old, corresponding to the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, meaning six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not on average accepted because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mud fevers are rampant, they are excluded for one year.
"With these 3% we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Weaknesses are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
But convincing people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unbridled today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood," Francine Décary writes.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québek, who also manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
The umbilical cord previously considered biomedical waste has blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000th sample of blood from the umbilical cord to the bank, and we expect to collect over a thousand a year.
In the early next year, we should start offering them for transplants," Dr. Décary explains, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," as Hema-Québec does not have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
