Opinions - Orwell discurs from Barrick Gold
In a September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the largest gold producer in the world has launched prosecutions of three authors and a poor little publishing house for libel in order to spark a "transparent public debate", demanding six million of them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truth, especially in the case of prosecutions for libel, but the law.
It is no surprise that Garver is completely passing away this fundamental distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to conduct a public debate to bring down anyone who dares defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend themselves and fight in a very uneven fight with an army of lawyers supported by almost bottomless pockets of mining company.
After all, tactics in these unbalanced struggles often consist in the overthrow of defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will plug the mouth of the counterparty and, moreover, dismay anyone who dares to pursue this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her view of the whole thing to public opinion.
In contrast to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, Canada has a debate in normal circumstances in the exchange of ideas rather than in baton wounds.
Thus, mining companies were not enough to open up their books, their documentation, and establish real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and funding for independent scientific teams that could shed light on the whole thing.
However, Barrick Gold does not seem to have confidence in public opinion and squeamishly reject petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada's book.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he could demand a 'public debate' and at the same time despise the opinion of the same public?
It seems that this word in the vice president's world only refers to fat-paid lawyers, and not all Canadians; that is a rather narrowed concept of that term.
In democracy, even nacturers have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public, who supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, does so primarily because he rejects the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is prepared to hear and judge the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not as part of what many perceive as prosecutions in which the defendant is to be blocked by his mouth (as part of his prosecution of the "public debate" by the way, Barrick has just presented an official call to the authors of Noir Canada to officially announce to them that they should stop using this term...).
Apart from the surreal Garver speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on university freedom of inquiry and the search for the truth that are essential to every democratic society.
Overall, he denies the right to citation of credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations that constitute the basis of intellectual activity itself.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to study and discuss topics that do not like the rich companies of this world without being subjected to repeated prosecutions, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could create it if she followed the scientific standards used by Noir Canada's authors.
He has the right to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's exaggerated lawsuit clearly shows that despite what he claims, he has no desire to conduct a transparent debate.
For the university world, it is a loss, as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to introduce measures that would limit such a type of unauthorized prosecution.
