In particular, it assumes: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms ensuring the repayment of the public money deposited, new measures to capture the number of houses seized due to default and also the right to monitor the amount of wages paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news yesterday minutes after midnight, after the conclusion of the two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and we have reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the Wall Street crisis," the Democrat explained.
"This is a crucial point: if we do not do this, trauma, chaos and disruption of everyday American life will be huge," Republican Judd Gregg said.
During the last hours, negotiations have started at maximum speeds for fear of the effect of further failures to develop investors.
The time limit was to open the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the U.S. President were invited to negotiate later, and both expressed themselves rather in favour of the agreement, but did not neglect to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited himself with supplementing the agreement on certain measures, in particular those aimed at allowing the owners to maintain their residence, and those on wages leading the labor state of the rescued companies.
"When we ask the taxpayers to take special measures due to the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate ourselves on.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on television waves.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The crude features I have read [showing] that it is something that we will all have to spend and with which it will be possible to move forward.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The aim of the 700-million-dollar plan is to buy out doubtful claims and risk and unsaleable assets from US financial institutions with taxpayers' money.
The plan comes after a 14-month crisis unleashed by a bursting housing bubble that first led to a collapse of risk mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in a freezing of cash and in the dissolution of banks and financial institutions.
The decline in the first draft agreement last week was caused by Republican MPs.
From the moment the Democrats agreed that the government would only guarantee some "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty, but not buy them, there is a belief that the impasse situation is averted.
In an effort to bring conflicting views closer together in Congress, a measure was added stating that the government would be able to introduce new fees to help her regain her deposit if, as a result of the program, she would have to assume losses for five years.
The new plan envisages a deposit of the first amount of 250 billion, to which it will be possible to add an additional 100 billion if the President considers it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire shares in saved companies that, in the event of profits, will pay him dividends and which he will be able to sell again when this is over.
The Federal Government will be able to delay the procedures for seizure of the properties associated with the loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits for the amount of valuation and compensation paid to the managers of the affected firms.
The designers of the plan would like to put him to the vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain whether their plan will be green.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against this project in both Republican and Democratic camp.
"It is quite obvious that Washington can't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Financial Commission, declared to the electorate.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
However, profiting on taxpayers is not the answer."
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, the presenter of a group of congressmen dubbed "the Skeptic Committee", presents the whole matter differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred respected professors of economics, among them three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and to scrutinize carefully which way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis was a global crisis.
After the end of the emergency meeting, three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the banking group Fortis for EUR 11.2 billion (US$1.3 billion).
The intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from buying its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapsing since it lost €2 billion ($2.9 billion) as a result of the risk-credit crisis in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people, among the 20 largest European banks and among the ten largest insurers.
"We will not lose this money," said Dutch finance minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
"In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And that is what savers and households can appreciate in these uncertain times."
On the other side of the Channel La Manche so far, the British government seems to have launched the nationalization of another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, of which more than USD 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) constituted loans to buy real estate.
According to his announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy out the branches and accounts of British bank clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock, which the British government must nationalize from the beginning of the financial crisis.
