According to the prosecutor, they used the money obtained in public competitions for their own purposes and often documented the fulfilment of tasks with fictitious invoices.
Money from the state and self-government - totalling approximately 65 million forints - went partly to Fiatal Ballodal's treasury, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The manner in which the investigating authority also informed the investigating authority was that the money received in the public competitions was collected on the basis of invoices which were not a real consideration and the undertakings accepted were never met by the associations.
According to the prosecution, much of the invoices were fake.
Forms for these invoices came from the Yozsefros market, round stamps were produced in Kiskunhalasi.
The names of which companies are to produce invoices were decided, among other things, on a tour route along the northern bank of Balaton, on which István Ladose János Zuschlag sent.
According to his statement, he was to look for the first-named boarding houses and restaurants.
In them, he requested accounts for his consumption, according to which the invoices submitted in public competitions were then produced by, inter alia, the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and, respectively, the Self-government of the capital.
Most of the invoices were exhibited by István Lados with his associate András ‹rim, who, according to our information, most often wrote the news needed to obtain subsidies.
On his "study trip", Lados looked at a beerhouse.
