Psychology of trumping: why are we spending more money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate goods.
Neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed to researchers in the field of neurology and economics of the University of New York.
According to their study, published in Science magazine, people do not want to fall behind in the eBay auction competition, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
Research, using an experimental auction, attempted to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in the stage auction, using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method being examined by active areas of the brain of experimental persons.
In both games, participants could win money, but in the auction game, the important element of which is to trump the other side, a whole under the cerebral cortex, called striatum, began to function intensively in losing.
In addition to many other functions, this brain area plays a role in the "self-remuneration" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to researchers, price unscrewing can therefore be explained by trying to avoid a sharp reaction of the striatus.
To support their theories, members of the research team from the economists conducted a financial cross-cutting survey.
In doing so, three groups were citing against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product and they made bets.
In addition, members of another group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would receive $15 more for the reward.
On the contrary, the third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members lost this money as well.
Thus, the difference between the two groups was all in all that one was stressed by winning and the other by losing.
However, members of the group playing "against loss" were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the neurologist hypothesis.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
These have so far explained phenomena observable in auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the contradiction between these two theories so that we have now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Economic Faculty of New York University.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infections, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated, causing sick people often not to know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms, there are many similarities, typical of liver inflammation and jaundice, but the origins of the disease and the disease caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main ways, depending on the underlying diseases: hepatitis A and E to the digestive tract (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travelers should in any case be protected by vaccination against A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against a C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after taking an infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal distress, urge to vomit.
After this, jaundice, light stool, and dark urine are produced on the skin and eye whites. The treatment may take two to three weeks.
Every year, millions of people around the world die of a more serious type of this disease, liver cancer, and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in 10 infected patients is treated medically.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated, it may lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected with their illness do not even know the cause of the disease destroys liver cells insidiously, so the first symptoms occur in many cases up to 20-30 years.
It is therefore very important to prevent early, implement regular deputations.
In three groups, this disease occurs a lot more often than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion prior to 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can already prove routine laboratory testing, a person should contact his or her physician if he or she notices any sign of unknown origin.
In early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the organism to prevent contagiousness and prevent cancer from occurring.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, which was organized by organizations representing the sick for the first time worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, to the causes of its formation and to the importance of early detection of the disease.
Who believes in God doesn't hurt so much?
According to recent research, faith in God acts as an analgesic that could have facilitated the death of already Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment, researching how faith in the god of pain affects man, informed the British daily Telegraph.
As part of a rather bizarre survey, they subjected 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists to electric shocks while all observed the painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the pain.
The technique of examining the human brain also showed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for controlling pain.
Research is the first of a series of researches involving scientists, philosophers, and theologians from various parts of the university alongside academics.
The exact test took place by attaching a sparking instrument to the left hand of the test subject, which issued electrical shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to observe the two paintings intently: Sassoferrat's Virgin Mary from the 17th century and the Lady with the Edge of Leonard da Vinci, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that the view of Our Lady would create a certain state of piety among believers, while Da Vinci's image was chosen because they did not differ too much from the first and seem to make a calming impression.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in the MRI scanner and during this time received in four consecutive parts 20 electroshocks, while separately watching the picture with religious or general topics.
Catholics stated that when they looked at Our Lady, they felt "safe", as if they were "taken care of" and "calmed down, filled with peace".
In observing the painting with religious thematics, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they had Leonard’s work before them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved using any strongly impressive image even in atheists, just to find the right photograph.
"We would have to find an image that they will perceive very positively, from the position of mother or father," said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases it will also change our personality," Wright added.
After such great results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on the regulation of the pain of believers if they showed them some Madonna from Leonard or a painter of similar caliber.
Would the view of the quality Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
