Intelligent Car Imitates Bumblebee Flight
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collision, if not imitation of barriers detectors occurring in the world of nature?
Bees, for example.
The initial strategic idea of the surprise project, presented at the Japan fair CEATEC, was inspired by engineers from Nissan bumblebees. It was about how to build a new generation of collision prevention systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan designed a biomimetic robotic system of BR23C-type management, a robotized minicar that is equipped with bee characteristics, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate any precipitation.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety protective cover," Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of the brand for technological PR and research and development.
Composite eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see into all directions at a visual angle of more than 300 degrees.
Engineers were able to copy the function of the folded eye after the idea of a laser distance meter.
It identifies obstacles at a distance of up to 2 metres in front of BR23C in a 180 degree field of vision, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms into an operation aimed at preventing collision.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotized car begins to mimic the movements of the bee and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver takes place in an absolutely instinctive way.
"If that were not the case, a robotic car could not respond quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
They must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety cover, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not last longer than a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotation, acceleration and deceleration was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer accumulators that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, an instinctive, intelligent response is important, not the processing ability, the less data storage.
This mechanism must only process and respond to several incoming signals per second.
There is no need for him to preserve them and respond using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, therefore he is constantly using only a memory of the size of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with a giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing an immediate avoidance technology that, according to Nissan's estimate, could reach serial-produced vehicles within ten years.
Another option of application may be to connect the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the motorist to the specified final target after avoiding obstacles.
