"With the progress made last night, we are satisfied and very much appreciate both sides' efforts to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy," said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
After all, the program differs from the Bush administration's original proposal, which was intended to make the purchase of low-quality mortgage-backed securities spend an entire sum of $700 billion at once.
It is now possible to spend a maximum of half of $700 billion in the first round, by using 250 billion immediately after Congress is expected to decide on Monday, and the Treasury will buy mortgage-backed securities, which are rated as unquality, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will then depend on the president's decision.
The program will be controlled by a special corps, the member of which will also be the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank.
Spending the second half of $700 billion will depend on Congress' next decision.
The Ministry of Finance can apply the combined tactics within the meaning of the Act: it can simultaneously buy off poor-quality loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, or other "poison" loans.
The purchase can take place within auctions and directly, the competent representatives of the Ministry have informed.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme in which the Ministry of Finance grants them a guarantee for means of providing cause for concern, for which the company will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of the expected damage.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to meet the urgent demands of the U.S. financial system to spend up to $700 billion, whether it is a large purchase of bad funds, their insurance, or the prevention of systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the large cash institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be prepared to implement the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the contrary, the heads of banks that have come into trouble and are waiting to help the state can count on the government to cut their severance payments - which is simply called a "gold parachute" in overseas slang.
