Domestic sales prices in the industry rose 0.1 percent in August 2008 due to the previous month, then by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office announced.
Export sales prices in the industry were 1.1 percent higher compared to July 2008, decreasing year-on-year by 3.9 percent.
Production prices in the industry were 0.7 percent higher as a result of changes in domestic and export prices compared to the previous month, increasing by 3.2 percent yoy.
Domestic sales prices in the industry rose by at least 0.1 percent due to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sector also increased slightly, by 0.1 percent, compared to July.
The largest price increase took place in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 percent), mainly due to a month-on-month increase in prices in the luggage and saddlery products sector by 4.6 percent, respectively, and in footwear production by 2.5 percent.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused significant monthly price increases in the chemical and product production sector (1.6 percent).
The prices were reduced in the oil industry (1.4 percent), the production of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood sector (0.1 percent).
Prices in paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other manufacturing sectors, we have measured the price increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sectors, which have a large weight in the domestic sales of the industry, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly by the continued effect of the officially established increase in gas prices as of 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison of domestic sales in each manufacturing sector, prices increased most in the oil industry (32.4 percent).
In the co-production sector, 13,2 % could be observed, in the production of food products, beverages and tobacco products, which are of decisive importance, then an 11 % increase in prices.
The prices decreased in the textile and textile industries (2.5 percent) and in the electrical machinery and apparatus production (0.3 percent).
In other manufacturing sectors, the price growth rate ranged between 0.6% and 9.1%.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry increased by 10.2 percent over the last year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water industries exceeded prices from the previous year by 18.7 percent.
From the point of view of the sector's focus, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) in the material asset production sector was reflected in domestic sales in August.
Prices rose by 0.3 percent in the consumer-goods sector, in energy processing and further processing industries, prices did not change due to the previous month.
The largest price increase in respect of the same month of the previous year was observed in August 2008 in energy processing and further processing industries (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods sector, we have measured an increase in prices of 6.8 percent, while in the case of tangible assets, we have measured a fall in prices of 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, and decreased by 3.9 percent in the 12-month comparison.
Our domestic currency weakened 1.7 percent in relation to the euro in one month, then 7.1 percent in relation to the dollar, increased 7.5 percent in relation to the euro in comparison to the euro in August 2007 and 15.9 percent in relation to the dollar.
